07010nam a22010935i 9783110343939DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20142014gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2013557418  a(OCoLC)979912339  a97831103439397 a10.1515/97831103439392doi  a(DE-B1597)246069  a(OCoLC)890071031  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aPN2589b.I43 2014 7aLIT0041302bisacsh00a“If Then the World a Theatre Present…“ :bRevisions of the Theatrum Mundi Metaphor in Early Modern England /ced. by Björn Quiring. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPluralisierung & Autorität ,x2076-8281 ;v3200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tHaving a Good Time at the Theatre of the World: Amusement, Antitheatricality and the Calvinist Use of the Theatrum Mundi Metaphor in Early Modern England -- t“Out, out, brief candle”: Shakespeare and the Theatrum Mundi of Hospitality -- tPortraits of Hydra: Theatre and the Many-Headed Multitude -- t“They Have Their Exits and Their Entrances” On Two Basic Operations in the Theatrum Mundi -- t“Look on the Tragic Loading of this Bed”: Performing Community and its Other in Shakespeare’s Othello -- tA Narrow Thing Within One Word The Foreclosure of Nature in Post-Shakespearian Worlds and Times -- tDoubtful Visibilities The Theatrum Mundi of the German Baroque Trauerspiel -- tMetaphysical Skepticism, Incertitude and the Dissolution of the Theatrum Mundi -- tTheatrum Mundi and the Politics of Rebellion in Seventeenth-Century Drama -- tThe End of a Trope for the World0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTo metaphorize the world as a theatre has been a common procedure since antiquity, but the use of this trope became particularly prominent and pregnant in early modern times, especially in England. Old and new applications of the “theatrum mundi” topos pervaded discourses, often allegorizing the deceitfulness and impermanence of this world as well as the futility of earthly strife. It was frequently woven into arguments against worldly amusements such as the stage: Commercial theatre was declared an undesirable competitor of God’s well-ordered world drama. Early modern dramatists often reacted to this development by appropriating the metaphor, and in an ingenious twist, some playwrights even appropriated its anti-theatrical impetus: Early modern theatre seemed to discover a denial of its own theatricality at its very core. Drama was found to succeed best when it staged itself as a great unmasking. To investigate the reasons and effects of these developments, the anthology examines the metaphorical uses of theatre in plays, pamphlets, epics, treatises, legal proclamations and other sources.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aEnglish dramay17th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish dramayEarly modern and Elizabethan, 1500-1600xHistory and criticism. 0aTheater -- England -- History -- 16th century. 0aTheater and societyzEnglandxHistoryy16th century. 0aTheater and societyzEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aTheaterzEnglandxHistoryy16th century. 0aTheaterzEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 4aMetaphorologie. 4aShakespeare, William. 4aTheater. 4aWelttheater. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh  aMetaphorology.  aShakespeare, William.  aTheatre.  aTheatrum Mundi.1 aHarries, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaverkamp, Anselm, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHöfele, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLupton, Julia Reinhard, econtributor.